 society from the founders to the latest immigrants. Germans in Pennsylvania, Swiss in Georgia, Minorcans in Florida, Italians in Arkansas, French in Kansas, Chinese in California—all contributed to the domestication of Bacchus in the New World. So too did innumerable individuals, institutions, and organizations. Prominent politicians, obscure farmers, eager amateurs, sober scientists: these and all the other kinds and conditions of American men and women figure in the story. The history of wine in America is, in many ways, the history of American origins and of American enterprise in microcosm.While much of that history has been lost to sight, especially after Prohibition, the recovery of the record has been the goal of many investigators over the years, and the results are here brought together for the first time.In print in its entirety for the first time, A History of Wine in America is the most comprehensive account of winemaking in the United States, from the Norse discovery of native grapes in 1001 A.D., through Prohibition, and up to the present expansion of winemaking in every state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWine and wine makingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWine industryzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWine. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aamerican wine.  abacchus.  abest grapes for wine.  acalifornia wines.  aenglish settlers.  afarming.  ahistory of wine.  aimmigrants.  aimmigration.  aitalian explorer.  anative grapes.  anew world.  anorth american wine.  aoregon pinot noir.  aprohibition.  apromise of wine.  avikings and wine in america.  avineyards.  avinland.  awinemaking history.  awineries.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Pre